subsection.p:
Your task. Choose one field and one closed curve.
\begin{array}{c|c} \text{Field} \amp \text{Feature} \\ \hline \mathbf F=(-y,x) \amp \text{constant positive scalar curl }2\\[1mm] \mathbf F=\left(-\dfrac y2,\dfrac x2\right) \amp \text{work equals area}\\[4mm] \mathbf F=(2x,2y) \amp \text{gradient field}\\[1mm] \mathbf F=(y^2,x) \amp \text{nonconstant scalar curl}\\[1mm] \mathbf F=\left(\dfrac{-y}{x^2+y^2},\dfrac{x}{x^2+y^2}\right) \amp \text{punctured-plane warning} \end{array}
For curves, use a circle, ellipse, rectangle, triangle, or a piecewise smooth curve of your own.

Your task. Choose one surface.

  \begin{array}{c|c}
  \text{Surface} \amp \text{Suggested field} \\ \hline
  \text{paraboloid cap} \amp (x,y,z)\\[1mm]
  \text{hemisphere with disk base} \amp (0,0,z)\\[1mm]
  \text{cylinder side plus caps} \amp (x,y,1)\\[1mm]
  \text{box with one face removed} \amp (x^2,y,z)\\[1mm]
  \text{triangulated surface or mesh} \amp \text{constant or radial field}
  \end{array}

A seed example: four boundary points. Suppose a surveyor records four boundary points of a small field, measured in meters from a local reference point:
\begin{array}{c|cc} \text{Point} \amp x \amp y \\ \hline P_0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\ P_1 \amp 5 \amp 1\\ P_2 \amp 4 \amp 4\\ P_3 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{array}
Assume the points are listed counterclockwise and connected by straight segments.

